Analyzing Literature by Abstract Topic and Author Network¶

We mainly analyze the abstract by topic modeling using LDA models and authors' connections by visualizing networks.

Data Preprocessing¶

Get cleaned abstracts and authors and their mapping

In [3]:
cleaned_abstracts = []
for paper in papers:
    if paper["csl"] != None:
        if "abstract" in paper["csl"]:
            if paper["csl"]["abstract"] == None:
                paper["csl"]["abstract"] = ""
            abs = re.sub(r"<[^>]*>", "", paper["csl"]["abstract"])
            abs = re.sub("[^A-Za-z0-9' ]+", ' ', abs)
            cleaned_abstracts.append(abs)
            continue
    if paper["s2data"] != None:
        if "abstract" in paper["s2data"]:
            if paper["s2data"]["abstract"] == None:
                paper["s2data"]["abstract"] = ""
            abs = re.sub(r"<[^>]*>", "", paper["s2data"]["abstract"])
            abs = re.sub("[^A-Za-z0-9' ]+", ' ', abs)
            cleaned_abstracts.append(abs)

cleaned_authors = set()
author_paper_map = {}
for paper in papers:
    if paper["csl"] != None:
        for author in paper["csl"]["author"]:
            name = ""
            if 'given' in author and 'family' in author:
                name = author["given"] + " " + author["family"]
                cleaned_authors.add(name)
            else:
                if 'family' in author:
                    name = author['family']
                    cleaned_authors.add(name)
                else:
                    name = author['literal']
                    cleaned_authors.add(name)
            if name in author_paper_map:
                author_paper_map[name].append(papers.index(paper))
            else:
                author_paper_map[name] = [papers.index(paper)]
    else:
        for author in paper["s2data"]["authors"]:
            name = author['externalIds']['DBLP'][0]
            cleaned_authors.add(name)
            if name in author_paper_map:
                author_paper_map[name].append(papers.index(paper))
            else:
                author_paper_map[name] = [papers.index(paper)]
                
cleaned_authors = list(cleaned_authors)

View Abstract in a High Level¶

We present the abstract via word cloud, seeing what the dataset is mainly about. We anticipate that we will see keywords related to scholarly communication because this is what this course is about.

In [4]:
def plot_cloud_author(author):
    words = ""
    for paperId in author_paper_map[author]:
        words += cleaned_abstracts[paperId] + ". "
    if len(words) < 20:
        print("Not enough words")
    else:
        plot_cloud(words)

def plot_cloud(words):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width=960, height=640, random_state=1, background_color='salmon', colormap='Pastel1', collocations=False, stopwords = STOPWORDS).generate(words)
    # Set figure size
    plt.figure(figsize=(4, 3))
    # Display image
    plt.imshow(wordcloud) 
    # No axis details
    plt.axis("off");

plot_cloud(" ".join(cleaned_abstracts))
sample_authors = ["Jeffrey Heer", "Daniel S. Weld", "Dominik Moritz", "Andrew Head", "Anhong Guo"]
print("Word Cloud for sample authors:")
print(sample_authors)
for author in sample_authors:
    plot_cloud_author(author)

Topic Modeling via LDA¶

By using topic modeling we can create clusters of documents that are relevant. Here we use pyLDAvis, an open-source python library that helps in analyzing and creating highly interactive visualization of the clusters created by LDA.

In [5]:
abstracts_for_analysis = []
for abs in cleaned_abstracts:
    temp_abs = abs.split(' ')
    abstracts_for_analysis.append([w for w in temp_abs if w.lower() not in STOPWORDS and w != "\n" and w != '✔' and w != ""])

abstract_dict = corpora.Dictionary(abstracts_for_analysis)
abstract_corpus = [abstract_dict.doc2bow(text) for text in abstracts_for_analysis]
lda = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus=abstract_corpus, id2word=abstract_dict, num_topics=10, random_state=100, update_every=1, chunksize=100, passes=10, alpha='auto', per_word_topics=True)
pyLDAvis.enable_notebook()
pyLDAvis.gensim_models.prepare(lda, abstract_corpus, abstract_dict)

Visualizing Authors Connections¶

For co-authorships, we visualize authors' connections using a force-directed graph.

In [6]:
connections = {}
max_conn = 0
for author1 in author_paper_map:
    for author2 in author_paper_map:
        if author1 == author2:
            continue
        common = list(set(author_paper_map[author1]).intersection(author_paper_map[author2]))
        if len(common) > 0:
            if (author1, author2) not in connections and (author2, author1) not in connections:
                connections[(author1, author2)] = len(common)
                if len(common) > max_conn:
                    max_conn = len(common)

G = nx.Graph()
for conn in connections:
    G.add_edge(conn[0], conn[1], weight = connections[conn])
net = Network(notebook=True, width=1000, height=600)
# load the networkx graph
net.from_nx(G)
# show
net.show("ex.html")
